Ezzat Ghoniem is an Egyptian human rights lawyer and activist. He defended people who were arrested or abused by the state and spoke out about police violence and unfair trials. In 2018, he was forcibly disappeared for several days before reappearing in custody. He was later accused of spreading false news and supporting a banned group, charges often used in Egypt to silence critical voices. After briefly being released, he disappeared again under unclear circumstances and has not been reliably seen since.

His case shows how defending basic rights can put someone at risk in certain countries. When communication is monitored, even organizing legal defense or sharing case details becomes dangerous. In such situations, discreet tools that don’t rely on public networks or keep visible records reduce exposure. Key ideas include forced disappearance, targeted surveillance, human rights defense under authoritarian rule, and digital self-protection.